2. Design Overview 
2.1 Process Control Block (PCB) 
The PCB represents a process in the system. In this assignment, each PCB contains: 
● A unique integer process ID 
● An integer priority value (1–50) 
● A process state (NEW, READY, RUNNING, WAITING, or TERMINATED) 
When a PCB is first created, it is initialized in the NEW state. The PCB class provides simple 
accessor and mutator functions to retrieve and update its attributes. State transitions are 
handled by other components (such as the ReadyQueue) according to the assignment 
requirements. 
2.2 PCB Table 
The PCBTable stores all PCBs currently existing in the system. It is implemented as a container 
of dynamically allocated PCB objects (e.g., an array or list of PCB*). 
The PCBTable is responsible for: 
● Creating new PCBs 
● Providing access to PCBs by index or ID 
● Releasing all dynamically allocated memory when the table is destroyed 
Special care was taken to ensure that all allocated PCBs are properly deleted in the destructor 
to avoid memory leaks. 
2.3 Ready Queue 
The ReadyQueue represents the set of processes that are ready to be scheduled on the CPU. It 
is implemented as a priority queue, where the process with the highest priority is always 
selected first. 
To meet the assignment constraints, no STL containers (such as priority_queue or vector) 
were used in the ReadyQueue implementation. Instead, a custom data structure was chosen to 
efficiently support priority-based scheduling. 
The ReadyQueue supports the following operations: 
● addPCB(PCB*): Inserts a PCB into the queue and sets its state to READY 
● removePCB(): Removes and returns the PCB with the highest priority and sets its state 
to RUNNING 
● size(): Returns the number of PCBs in the queue 
● displayAll(): Displays the IDs and priorities of all PCBs in the queue 
3. Data Structure Choice and Time Complexity 
The priority range of PCBs is limited to values between 1 and 50. This constraint allows for 
efficient implementation choices. 
The ReadyQueue is implemented using a structure that groups PCBs by priority level. This 
design allows fast insertion and efficient selection of the highest-priority process. 
Time Complexity Analysis 
Let n be the total number of processes currently in the ReadyQueue. 
● Insertion (addPCB): O(1) 
A PCB is directly placed into the structure corresponding to its priority. 
● Removal (removePCB): O(50) → effectively O(1) 
The queue is scanned from highest to lowest priority to find the next available PCB. 
Since the priority range is fixed, this operation runs in constant time. 
● Display (displayAll): O(n) 
All PCBs in the queue are traversed and displayed. 
This design is well suited for operating-system scheduling, where fast insertion and predictable 
removal times are critical. 
4. Testing and Performance Evaluation 
4.1 Correctness Testing (test1) 
The test1 program verifies the correctness of the ReadyQueue implementation by performing 
a sequence of insertions and removals with known priorities. The program displays the contents 
of the ReadyQueue after each operation. 
The output produced by our implementation exactly matches the expected output in 
test1_out.txt, confirming that the ReadyQueue correctly maintains priority order and 
updates process states as required. 
4.2 Performance Testing (test2) 
The test2 program evaluates performance under heavy workload conditions. It creates 500 
PCBs with random priorities and repeatedly performs random insert and remove operations on 
the ReadyQueue for 1,000,000 iterations. 
With compiler optimizations enabled (-O2 or -O3), the program completes execution in under 
one second. The observed runtime aligns with the expected constant-time behavior of the 
ReadyQueue operations, validating the efficiency of the chosen data structure. 
Because the operations involve randomness, the final content of the ReadyQueue may differ 
from the sample output, which is expected behavior. 
